n the perceptions and histories of Israel’s most marginalized stakeholders—Palestinian Israelis, Arab Jews, and non-Israeli Jews—Atalia Omer cuts to the heart of the Israeli-Arab conflict, demonstrating how these voices provide urgently needed resources for conflict analysis and peacebuilding. Navigating a complex set of arguments about ethnicity, boundaries, and peace, and offering a different approach to the renegotiation and reimagination of national identity and citizenship, Omer pushes the conversation beyond the bounds of the single narrative and toward a new and dynamic concept of justice—one that offers the prospect of building a lasting peace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArab-Israeli conflictxSocial aspects. 0aArab-Israeli conflicty1993-xPeace. 0aGroup identityzIsrael. 0aPeace movementszIsrael. 70(DE-601)1048262900(DE-588)4041158-8aNahostkonflikt2gnd 70(DE-601)1055159140(DE-588)4155429-2aFriedensbemühung2gnd 70(DE-601)1063254690(DE-588)4018520-5aFriedensbewegung2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apeace, israeli, israel, religion, religious studies, nationalism, justice, injustice, middle east, jewish, haven, safety, faith, belief, adversity, liberal, nation, nationhood, citizenship, citizen, stakeholder, palestinian, arab, race, racism, ethnic group, ethnicity, boundaries, renegotiation, reimagination, borders, 1990s, contemporary, modern, academic, scholarly, research, zionist, alterity, mizrahim, human rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022600807340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226008240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226008240/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c